@stevetobias4890    There is a basic similarity in that both materials require fairly high heating in an oxygen deprived environment.

   But C-CNC can be made more sustainably and cheaply.  And if you make a super solar oven like I'm making, it becomes much cheaper/more sustainable.  A little goes a long way with C-CNC. 

  It's tensile and young modulus strengths are much higher than average carbon fiber. when the CNC is carbonized.  Even raw CNC has the same tensile strength and a bit more stiffness strength.

@btryba    Some of the formulations I've seen for bioplastic include adding some vinegar.  
   Even if you get it relatively water resistant--it won't be a great substitute for fiberglass/epoxy since these have much higher tensile, Young's modulus, etc strengths.  
  With that said, adding crystalline nanocellulose, in both the raw, and especially in the carbonized form, will greatly increase those various strengths.

